Roc Road is the primary overland trade corridor connecting Midgaard (east) to Kiess (west), built on at least four historical strata: a pre-city migration track following ridge-and-valley geography, a formalized stone route with mile markers and drainage channels from a predecessor polity, a war-era military supply corridor, and a post-war mercantile reconstruction spine. Kiess was built on the ruins of Evermeet, which formerly anchored the western end; Evermeet's collapse left the western terminus without a stable partner for a generation. The road currently functions through overlapping institutions that do not fully trust each other: Midgaard road wardens maintain formal watch protocols and legal seals while Kiess convoy marshals control actual traffic flow west of the Crossroads. The Continuity faction maintains the road has been under continuous Midgaard charter authority since the Stone Law Period; the Reckoning faction cites the Unindexed Years — missing ledger pages from the late Containment Era — as evidence the charter was abandoned during the Evermeet Collapse. The Granite Arcade trade ledger entry "forty iron bars and six condemned debtors" transferred to "the mountain academy" implicates Roc Road as a condemned-prisoner corridor during the Continuity era. During the Evermeet Collapse, the road became a displacement corridor: refugees flooded eastward, toll cairns became emergency rationing points, and military requisitioners used road infrastructure originally built for tariff collection. Midgaard's Three Civic Oaths are recited by road wardens at every shift change on the eastern half. Kiess convoy compacts bind caravan operators, hired guards, and waystation custodians into shared liability pools. The road is stable enough to be indispensable, unstable enough to remain dangerous.

