Kowloon has no direct charter presence on Roc Road, which runs east-west between Midgaard and Kiess while Kowloon sits north of Midgaard.
Kowloon's interest is as the western extension of the Midgaard trade network that the Lantern Road connects northward to Kowloon's markets.
When Roc Road is stable, Kiess-origin goods flow through Midgaard to the Lantern Road and northward; when disrupted, Midgaard's western supply suffers, affecting Midgaard's capacity to trade northward.
Kowloon's Courier Lantern Office receives Roc Road status reports through Kiess's relay station and through Midgaard's warden intelligence channels.
The road's dual-authority structure is viewed from Kowloon as a less functional arrangement than the Great Northern Forest's neutral-ground commission governance, which allows disputes to be resolved without either city holding a trump card.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess built its institutional identity partly in opposition to the road's history.
The founding charter's predecessor-warrant repudiation was written because the road had been used as a transfer corridor for condemned persons under Evermeet's legal framework.
The convoy compact system — shared liability pools, route ledgers tracking debt and loss, convoy marshals controlling traffic flow west of the Crossroads — is the Kiess response to the gap between Midgaard's charter claims and practical road operations during weak-state periods.
West of the Crossroads, Kiess practice is the only authority that matters when wagons are burning, regardless of Midgaard charter law.
The road's dual-mark manifest requirement (Midgaard wax and Kiess thread-knot) reduced smuggling fraud but institutionalized Kiess as co-equal road authority — a status Midgaard's Continuity faction does not formally recognize and Kiess's convoy marshals enforce daily.
